\begin{alertblock}{Summary}
Why must \textbf{sexual reproduction} persist in nature given its \textbf{twofold cost}? The \textbf{Red Queen Hypothesis} predicts sexually reproducing individuals to overcome the cost of sex by escaping infection more easily under strong parasite selection. Here, we tried to quantify the effect of the Red Queen and perform a power analysis.
\end{alertblock}

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%	QUICK REVISION
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\begin{block}{Evolution of sex}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Two fold cost of sex}: (1) cost of producing males and (2) cost of meiosis
    \item the two fold cost of cost of sex asumes that \textbf{all else is equal}
    \item only 0.01\% eukaryotes conform to purely asexual reproduction. How?
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

\begin{block}{Red Queen Hypothesis}
\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{McKone.png}\\
McKone \etal\ \cite{mckone2016fine}
\end{figure}
\begin{itemize}
    \item sexual reproduction creates rare genotypes that can escape infection (\textbf{negative frequncy dependence})
    \item snail population in New Zealand (host for sterilizing trematode infection) is believed to support the hypothesis
    \item prevalence of sex should be positively correlated with prevalence of infection
    \item unable to detect any correlation in a similar snail-trematode system \cite{dagan2013clonal}
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

